oyage through the deep history and present course of this sea change—a change that has seen species depleted, ecosystems devastated, and artisanal fisheries transformed into a global industry afloat with hundreds of billions of dollars per year. Bailey knows these waters, the artisanal fisheries, and their relationship with larger ocean ecology intimately. In a series of place-based portraits, he shares stories of decline and success as told by those at the ends of the long lines and hand lines, channeling us through the changing dynamics of small-scale fisheries and the sustainability issues they face—both fiscal and ecological. We encounter Paolo Vespoli and his tiny boat, the Giovanni Padre,in the Gulf of Naples; Wenche, a sea Sámi, one of the indigenous fisherwomen of Norway; and many more. From salmon to abalone, the Bay of Fundy to Monterey and the Amazon, Bailey’s catch is no fish tale. It is a global story, casting a net across waters as vast and distinct as Puget Sound and the Chilean coast. Sailing across the world, Bailey explores the fast-shifting current of how we gather food from the sea, what we gain and what we lose with these shifts, and potential solutions for the murky passage ahead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSmall-scale fisheries. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  afisheries, oceans, conservation, pollution, overfishing, habitat, science, boats, technology, sustainability, environmentalism, fishermen, ecology, artisanal, ecosystem, species depletion, gulf of naples, small scale fishing, sea sami, indigenous, norway, fisherwomen, female, salmon, abalone, bay fundy, monterey, amazon, puget sound, chile, coast, foodways, salish, legoe, reefnets, keta, aqua farming, arapaima, nonfiction, biology, zoology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-P